1
00:00:10,010 --> 00:00:11,512
All right, Irona,

2
00:00:11,595 --> 00:00:14,515
are you sure you packed
everything I need for camp?

3
00:00:14,598 --> 00:00:16,684
Everything is in the bag, Master Richie.

4
00:00:16,767 --> 00:00:19,937
Fishing gear, bathing suits,
and your superhero night-light

5
00:00:20,020 --> 00:00:22,314
to keep you safe.

6
00:00:22,397 --> 00:00:25,776
- I don't need that anymore.
- Should I take it out?

7
00:00:25,860 --> 00:00:30,280
Ah, just keep it in the bag
and take it down to the car.

8
00:00:31,699 --> 00:00:33,659
I can't wait to get to camp.

9
00:00:33,742 --> 00:00:36,537
I'm going to be such
an emotional wreck without you.

10
00:00:36,620 --> 00:00:39,498
I'm going to be forced to distract myself.

11
00:00:39,581 --> 00:00:43,293
Speaking of which,
where are the yacht keys?

12
00:00:45,880 --> 00:00:50,342
I am ready for the great outdoors.

13
00:00:50,425 --> 00:00:54,221
Murray, why are you wearing
underwear on your head?

14
00:00:54,304 --> 00:00:56,431
Pfft. Why do you think?

15
00:00:56,515 --> 00:00:58,475
I honestly have no idea.

16
00:00:58,559 --> 00:01:02,354
This is my secret weapon
to keep away the camp bullies.

17
00:01:02,437 --> 00:01:05,273
The Abramowitz twins will see
this underwear ring

18
00:01:05,357 --> 00:01:08,527
and figure they already wedgied me.

19
00:01:08,610 --> 00:01:13,114
Ha, Abramowitzes, I wedgied myself.

20
00:01:15,743 --> 00:01:18,746
Why didn't you just cut the
ring off a pair of underwear?

21
00:01:18,829 --> 00:01:22,624
[scoffs]
Please, Richie, that...

22
00:01:22,708 --> 00:01:25,920
that would've been a better plan.

23
00:01:26,003 --> 00:01:28,087
Guys, did you hear the news
about camp?

24
00:01:28,171 --> 00:01:30,841
The rat infestation
isn't exactly news.

25
00:01:30,925 --> 00:01:33,969
It's just part of the rustic experience.

26
00:01:34,053 --> 00:01:35,846
I always liked the rats.

27
00:01:35,930 --> 00:01:38,640
They never gave me a wedgie.

28
00:01:38,724 --> 00:01:42,853
Nasty case of hemorrhagic fever
but no wedgie.

29
00:01:42,937 --> 00:01:45,022
No, Camp Bohawk burnt down.

30
00:01:45,064 --> 00:01:46,356
both: What?

31
00:01:46,440 --> 00:01:48,149
Oh, my gosh, what happened?

32
00:01:48,233 --> 00:01:49,526
Apparently, a camper wanted

33
00:01:49,610 --> 00:01:51,194
a really well-done s'more

34
00:01:51,278 --> 00:01:54,615
and, well, got it.

35
00:01:54,698 --> 00:01:56,575
[cash register dings]
My name is Richie Rich,

36
00:01:56,658 --> 00:01:57,910
and I'm just a normal kid--

37
00:01:57,993 --> 00:01:59,160
except that I have

38
00:01:59,244 --> 00:02:00,537
a trillion dollars.

39
00:02:00,621 --> 00:02:02,539
You see, I used
all the vegetables I never ate

40
00:02:02,623 --> 00:02:04,416
to create a new energy source

41
00:02:04,499 --> 00:02:06,501
and sold it for a lot of money.
[cha-ching]

42
00:02:06,585 --> 00:02:09,671
Now I live in a huge mansion
with my own amusement park,

43
00:02:09,755 --> 00:02:12,132
race car, and personal robot maid.

44
00:02:12,215 --> 00:02:14,175
And I have my family and
the best friends in the world

45
00:02:14,259 --> 00:02:15,594
to share my fortune with:

46
00:02:15,677 --> 00:02:16,929
My dad,

47
00:02:17,012 --> 00:02:18,472
my jealous sister, Harper,

48
00:02:18,555 --> 00:02:19,890
my money manager, Murray,

49
00:02:19,974 --> 00:02:22,183
and my money spender, Darcy.

50
00:02:22,267 --> 00:02:25,353
I guess you could say,
by not eating my vegetables,

51
00:02:25,437 --> 00:02:29,691
I became the richest
and luckiest kid in the world.

52
00:02:29,775 --> 00:02:32,235
This stinks--
now that camp is cancelled,

53
00:02:32,319 --> 00:02:37,116
I'm stuck spending the next two
weeks in this palatial mansion.

54
00:02:37,198 --> 00:02:41,244
[Swedish accent] 
Richie,I have your morning smoothie!

55
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:45,958
Oops, I forgot the garnish.

56
00:02:46,041 --> 00:02:50,921
I'm not really in the mood
for a meatball smoothie.

57
00:02:51,005 --> 00:02:52,923
Camp Bohawk burnt to the ground.

58
00:02:53,007 --> 00:02:54,967
I feel for those poor campers.

59
00:02:55,050 --> 00:02:58,219
Darcy, you care about others?

60
00:02:58,303 --> 00:03:01,015
I just know how much joy
the Abramowitzes get

61
00:03:01,098 --> 00:03:03,976
out of giving you wedgies.

62
00:03:04,059 --> 00:03:07,228
I'm hating seeing you so devumstated.

63
00:03:07,312 --> 00:03:09,397
If you can't go to camp,

64
00:03:09,481 --> 00:03:11,274
perhaps the camp can come to you.

65
00:03:11,358 --> 00:03:13,777
I-I guess we could have the camp here.

66
00:03:13,861 --> 00:03:15,194
We could be the counselors

67
00:03:15,278 --> 00:03:17,114
and give the kids the full experience.

68
00:03:17,196 --> 00:03:20,492
Ooh, and I can be one of the campers.

69
00:03:20,575 --> 00:03:25,080
I've always dreamt of living in a shoe.

70
00:03:25,164 --> 00:03:26,498
He's gonna be really disappointed

71
00:03:26,581 --> 00:03:28,792
when he finds out what camping is.

72
00:03:28,876 --> 00:03:31,586
This is great! Camp Bohawk is back!

73
00:03:31,670 --> 00:03:35,465
Just promise me you won't
invite the Abramowitzes.

74
00:03:35,549 --> 00:03:39,511
Too late, they're on their way.

75
00:03:39,594 --> 00:03:40,762
[cha-ching]

76
00:03:40,846 --> 00:03:42,723
Hey, Harper, want some popcorn?

77
00:03:42,806 --> 00:03:44,975
Fresh melted butter.

78
00:03:45,059 --> 00:03:46,601
You're drinking butter?

79
00:03:46,685 --> 00:03:48,812
Yeah, this way,
my hands don't get greasy.

80
00:03:48,896 --> 00:03:50,355
Pretty smart, huh?

81
00:03:50,438 --> 00:03:52,024
- Dad, what are you doing?
- Oh!

82
00:03:52,107 --> 00:03:53,734
I'm writing something really important,

83
00:03:53,817 --> 00:03:55,318
and it has to be done by tomorrow.

84
00:03:55,402 --> 00:03:56,820
[chuckles]

85
00:03:56,904 --> 00:03:58,739
If it's for school,
how important can it be?

86
00:03:58,822 --> 00:04:00,365
It's not for school.

87
00:04:00,448 --> 00:04:02,743
It's my final appeal
to the Harvard admission board.

88
00:04:02,826 --> 00:04:05,495
I'm drafting a 17-page letter
refuting the letter

89
00:04:05,579 --> 00:04:07,039
they sent me.

90
00:04:07,122 --> 00:04:10,000
"Leave us alone."

91
00:04:12,502 --> 00:04:15,296
Dad, you're spilling butter everywhere.

92
00:04:15,380 --> 00:04:17,007
Don't worry,
I got another pound and a half

93
00:04:17,091 --> 00:04:18,425
simmering on the stove.

94
00:04:18,508 --> 00:04:20,802
I'm not worried about your butter.

95
00:04:20,886 --> 00:04:23,346
I'm worried about my papers.

96
00:04:23,430 --> 00:04:24,639
[grunts]

97
00:04:24,723 --> 00:04:25,891
[sighs]

98
00:04:25,974 --> 00:04:28,894
[screams]

99
00:04:28,977 --> 00:04:32,147
Harper!

100
00:04:32,231 --> 00:04:33,982
Your papers.

101
00:04:34,066 --> 00:04:36,193
Ow.

102
00:04:36,276 --> 00:04:37,652
[cha-ching]

103
00:04:37,736 --> 00:04:40,822
So, campers, was that a fun nature hike?

104
00:04:40,906 --> 00:04:42,866
[all groan]

105
00:04:42,950 --> 00:04:47,121
How often do you get to see
a snail in its natural habitat?

106
00:04:47,204 --> 00:04:48,872
I don't know about the snails,

107
00:04:48,956 --> 00:04:52,209
but it was a great excuse
to try out my trail mix recipe.

108
00:04:52,292 --> 00:04:54,086
Those are just meatballs.

109
00:04:54,169 --> 00:04:57,380
And dirt-- I mixed in the trail.

110
00:04:59,007 --> 00:05:00,425
The thing is,

111
00:05:00,508 --> 00:05:03,887
the campers want to have more fun.

112
00:05:03,971 --> 00:05:06,848
Some of them are having fun.

113
00:05:11,352 --> 00:05:13,897
Those Abramowitzes are evil.

114
00:05:13,981 --> 00:05:15,398
Evil!

115
00:05:19,736 --> 00:05:22,990
So what is being next?

116
00:05:23,073 --> 00:05:25,366
Perhaps we could jet ski
around your wave pool.

117
00:05:25,450 --> 00:05:28,495
No, we never did that at Bohawk.

118
00:05:28,578 --> 00:05:30,497
But don't worry, what's more fun

119
00:05:30,580 --> 00:05:33,125
than sleeping outdoors under the stars?

120
00:05:33,208 --> 00:05:38,088
Oh, in Sweden we have a name
for people who sleep outside.

121
00:05:38,172 --> 00:05:40,423
Stupid.

122
00:05:40,507 --> 00:05:42,550
Well, we always had fun
doing it at Bohawk,

123
00:05:42,634 --> 00:05:43,969
so we're doing it here.

124
00:05:44,052 --> 00:05:46,180
Boys, we are sleeping in the tree house

125
00:05:46,263 --> 00:05:47,848
with Counselor Murray.

126
00:05:47,931 --> 00:05:51,768
Girls, you and Counselor Darcy
are in the pool shed.

127
00:05:51,852 --> 00:05:53,478
What?

128
00:05:53,561 --> 00:05:57,024
It's just the natural camp experience,

129
00:05:57,107 --> 00:06:00,443
with the faint hum of a Jacuzzi heater.

130
00:06:00,527 --> 00:06:01,820
[cha-ching]

131
00:06:01,903 --> 00:06:05,532
Dear Harvard.

132
00:06:06,908 --> 00:06:09,870
"Dfhernic hazarnic."

133
00:06:09,953 --> 00:06:12,455
Okay, let's try this again.

134
00:06:12,539 --> 00:06:16,626
[with tongue out]
Dear Harvard.

135
00:06:16,710 --> 00:06:19,296
I wish I tried those in reverse order.

136
00:06:19,378 --> 00:06:24,092
You think that's hard,
you should try drinking nachos.

137
00:06:24,176 --> 00:06:25,844
I mean, the cheese comes out fine,

138
00:06:25,927 --> 00:06:30,765
but these chips are playing hard to get.

139
00:06:30,849 --> 00:06:34,978
Dad, this may be the concussion talking,

140
00:06:35,062 --> 00:06:37,022
but could you help me type this letter?

141
00:06:37,105 --> 00:06:40,359
I'd be happy to help you type a letter.

142
00:06:40,441 --> 00:06:42,652
So which letter we talking?

143
00:06:42,736 --> 00:06:45,780
I know most of 'em.

144
00:06:45,864 --> 00:06:48,658
[cha-ching]

145
00:06:48,742 --> 00:06:50,035
Isn't this great?

146
00:06:50,118 --> 00:06:52,829
The nature, the fresh air, the peace and--

147
00:06:52,913 --> 00:06:56,333
[truck reversing]

148
00:06:56,415 --> 00:07:00,045
Sorry, I'm replacing all
200 mattresses in my guest wing

149
00:07:00,128 --> 00:07:02,589
with ultra-soft pillow tops.

150
00:07:02,672 --> 00:07:05,300
Well, time to hit the wood.

151
00:07:08,887 --> 00:07:12,515
Are you sure it is being safe
to sleep out here?

152
00:07:12,599 --> 00:07:14,268
Totally.

153
00:07:14,351 --> 00:07:17,478
Trust me, 
the only time I felt safe at camp

154
00:07:17,562 --> 00:07:20,607
was inside the cabin.

155
00:07:28,782 --> 00:07:32,369
No!

156
00:07:32,452 --> 00:07:34,579
[birds chirping]

157
00:07:34,662 --> 00:07:37,999
That was fun. Right, guys?

158
00:07:41,044 --> 00:07:43,380
Guys?

159
00:07:47,092 --> 00:07:48,718
[Swedish accent]
"The boys wanted to sleep

160
00:07:48,802 --> 00:07:50,262
"on the pillow tops.

161
00:07:50,345 --> 00:07:52,264
See you in the morning."

162
00:07:54,474 --> 00:07:57,394
[pop music]

163
00:07:57,477 --> 00:08:03,150
♪ ♪

164
00:08:03,233 --> 00:08:06,569
Darcy, you are getting smoked
like a meatball

165
00:08:06,653 --> 00:08:09,739
that is getting smoked.

166
00:08:09,823 --> 00:08:13,576
What is going on here?

167
00:08:13,660 --> 00:08:15,703
Oh, hey, Richie,

168
00:08:15,787 --> 00:08:18,915
we are in the middle
of our morning powwow.

169
00:08:18,999 --> 00:08:21,376
Powwow!

170
00:08:21,460 --> 00:08:24,545
Right, just like at Camp Bohawk.

171
00:08:24,629 --> 00:08:27,007
This is not a morning powwow.

172
00:08:27,090 --> 00:08:29,468
Pa-wow!

173
00:08:29,550 --> 00:08:33,180
I love this word.

174
00:08:33,263 --> 00:08:35,432
Kids are supposed to be singing songs.

175
00:08:35,515 --> 00:08:37,225
Come on, everyone.

176
00:08:37,309 --> 00:08:39,894
♪ Bohawk,
campfires every night ♪

177
00:08:39,978 --> 00:08:43,773
♪ Bohawk, not a firehouse in sight ♪

178
00:08:43,857 --> 00:08:47,402
How did we not see that fire coming?

179
00:08:47,486 --> 00:08:49,446
Richie, we were just trying to have fun.

180
00:08:49,529 --> 00:08:51,739
These kids paid good money to be here.

181
00:08:51,823 --> 00:08:53,741
What? We didn't charge them.

182
00:08:53,825 --> 00:08:55,369
Right.

183
00:08:55,452 --> 00:08:57,662
I don't know what I'm saying.

184
00:08:57,745 --> 00:08:59,164
Let's sing.

185
00:08:59,247 --> 00:09:01,375
♪ Bohawk, stop, drop, and roll ♪

186
00:09:01,458 --> 00:09:04,002
♪ Bohawk... ♪

187
00:09:04,085 --> 00:09:06,671
That's all I remember.

188
00:09:06,754 --> 00:09:11,385
Darcy, I will not let you
disrespect our camp anthem,

189
00:09:11,468 --> 00:09:13,761
and I will not let these kids miss out

190
00:09:13,845 --> 00:09:16,014
on the real camp experience.

191
00:09:16,097 --> 00:09:17,974
Okay, but if they ask
for their money back,

192
00:09:18,058 --> 00:09:21,561
I'm sending them to you.

193
00:09:21,644 --> 00:09:23,397
[cha-ching]

194
00:09:23,480 --> 00:09:25,065
[groans]

195
00:09:25,148 --> 00:09:26,483
Yeah.

196
00:09:26,566 --> 00:09:29,277
Okay, I'm ready to type for you.

197
00:09:29,361 --> 00:09:31,571
I can't believe I agreed to this.

198
00:09:31,654 --> 00:09:34,615
Relax, I have lots of computer experience.

199
00:09:34,699 --> 00:09:35,867
[sighs]

200
00:09:35,950 --> 00:09:38,995
How do you turn this thing on?

201
00:09:40,705 --> 00:09:42,665
Okay, just type what I say.

202
00:09:42,749 --> 00:09:44,959
"Dear Harvard."

203
00:09:58,432 --> 00:09:59,974
What was all of that?

204
00:10:00,058 --> 00:10:01,309
The gist.

205
00:10:01,393 --> 00:10:02,561
What do you mean, "The gist"?

206
00:10:02,643 --> 00:10:03,978
I just said, "Dear Harvard."

207
00:10:04,062 --> 00:10:05,355
I Bruced it up for you.

208
00:10:05,439 --> 00:10:06,773
"Bruced"?

209
00:10:06,856 --> 00:10:08,275
Sure, made it more memorable.

210
00:10:08,358 --> 00:10:09,568
Anyone who reads that

211
00:10:09,650 --> 00:10:11,111
is definitely not going to forget it.

212
00:10:11,194 --> 00:10:13,280
Ooh, how many Ps in hippopotamus?

213
00:10:13,363 --> 00:10:15,823
What? There is no need for that word.

214
00:10:15,907 --> 00:10:17,992
Ah, I'll just guess. Let's say 12.

215
00:10:18,076 --> 00:10:19,786
Okay, no, no, no, stop it! You're done!

216
00:10:19,869 --> 00:10:21,621
You're done. Delete it.

217
00:10:21,704 --> 00:10:23,081
Fine. Hey, I'm just trying to help.

218
00:10:23,164 --> 00:10:24,416
If you want me to delete it, I will.

219
00:10:24,499 --> 00:10:25,666
[whoosh]

220
00:10:25,750 --> 00:10:26,918
Is it gone?

221
00:10:27,001 --> 00:10:28,378
It sure is-- I hit "send,"

222
00:10:28,462 --> 00:10:30,380
which sends it to the delete folder.

223
00:10:35,427 --> 00:10:37,095
[cha-ching]

224
00:10:37,178 --> 00:10:39,764
I'm worried you guys
aren't getting the spirit

225
00:10:39,847 --> 00:10:41,141
of the whole camp thing.

226
00:10:41,224 --> 00:10:43,810
And since last night was such a disaster--

227
00:10:43,893 --> 00:10:45,228
Disaster for you.

228
00:10:45,312 --> 00:10:47,606
Sleeping on those pillow beds is better

229
00:10:47,730 --> 00:10:51,234
than sleeping in a shoe.

230
00:10:51,318 --> 00:10:53,278
While I have no idea what you're saying,

231
00:10:53,361 --> 00:10:57,365
I know you guys aren't getting
the Bohawk experience.

232
00:10:57,449 --> 00:10:59,493
Can you speed things along?

233
00:10:59,576 --> 00:11:03,704
The girls and I are getting mani-pedis.

234
00:11:03,788 --> 00:11:07,959
There are no mani-pedis at Camp Bohawk.

235
00:11:08,042 --> 00:11:10,795
All right, today is survival day.

236
00:11:10,878 --> 00:11:14,466
We will be learning
how to live off the land

237
00:11:14,549 --> 00:11:16,593
in my bedroom.

238
00:11:16,675 --> 00:11:17,844
I will be showing you

239
00:11:17,927 --> 00:11:21,306
two different kinds of wild berries.

240
00:11:21,389 --> 00:11:23,224
One is safe to eat.

241
00:11:23,308 --> 00:11:26,894
The other is extremely poisonous.

242
00:11:26,978 --> 00:11:29,314
Knowing the difference
could save your life.

243
00:11:29,397 --> 00:11:31,816
Save my life!

244
00:11:31,899 --> 00:11:33,151
Murray?

245
00:11:33,234 --> 00:11:34,611
What are you doing?

246
00:11:34,693 --> 00:11:37,780
The Abramowitzes made me play dress-up

247
00:11:37,864 --> 00:11:41,326
all night long.

248
00:11:41,409 --> 00:11:42,910
And the worst part is

249
00:11:42,994 --> 00:11:44,621
I look fabulous.

250
00:11:47,415 --> 00:11:51,628
Your mascara's running, sweetie.

251
00:11:51,710 --> 00:11:54,005
Murray, sit down.

252
00:11:54,088 --> 00:11:58,510
And don't forget to cross your legs.

253
00:11:58,593 --> 00:12:03,764
So, if you come across
hozzenberries and traifberries,

254
00:12:03,848 --> 00:12:05,850
just remember this little song.

255
00:12:05,933 --> 00:12:08,228
♪ if it's a traif, then you're safe ♪

256
00:12:08,311 --> 00:12:09,812
♪ if it's a hozzen... ♪

257
00:12:09,896 --> 00:12:12,773
get to the hospital immediately.

258
00:12:12,857 --> 00:12:18,071
So traifs are sweet, while hozzens are--

259
00:12:20,907 --> 00:12:22,534
Uh-oh.

260
00:12:22,617 --> 00:12:25,786
Don't worry, one of the four doctors I saw

261
00:12:25,870 --> 00:12:28,373
assured me I'm fine.

262
00:12:28,456 --> 00:12:31,543
So we can continue with survival day.

263
00:12:31,626 --> 00:12:34,295
[all groan]

264
00:12:34,379 --> 00:12:36,506
My eardrums are pretty swollen,

265
00:12:36,590 --> 00:12:40,051
but I think I heard some cheers.

266
00:12:40,134 --> 00:12:44,972
Glad to hear you're as excited
as I am to get to fire making.

267
00:12:45,056 --> 00:12:47,517
So, if you're out in the woods
and you want to start a fire...

268
00:12:47,601 --> 00:12:49,269
Bring matches.

269
00:12:49,352 --> 00:12:52,897
It's the only time it's okay
to play with them.

270
00:12:52,980 --> 00:12:56,067
And that concludes survival day.

271
00:13:00,321 --> 00:13:02,282
No, it doesn't.

272
00:13:02,365 --> 00:13:03,742
This is important stuff.

273
00:13:03,824 --> 00:13:06,494
I have to teach them
the proper technique.

274
00:13:06,578 --> 00:13:10,915
Come on, you stupid--

275
00:13:10,998 --> 00:13:12,709
great!

276
00:13:12,791 --> 00:13:16,546
Does anyone have another--

277
00:13:16,630 --> 00:13:19,424
Not again!

278
00:13:19,507 --> 00:13:20,759
[cha-ching]

279
00:13:20,841 --> 00:13:24,387
I so needed this, counselor Darcy.

280
00:13:24,471 --> 00:13:29,267
All those years of DJing has
done a number on my cubicles.

281
00:13:29,350 --> 00:13:31,519
I was thinking green would be really cute

282
00:13:31,603 --> 00:13:33,313
but not a heather green, more like a...

283
00:13:33,396 --> 00:13:35,356
What is going on in here?

284
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:37,317
That's the color.

285
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:40,654
You would look fantastic with
Richie's face on your nails.

286
00:13:42,656 --> 00:13:44,907
I'm really disappointed in you guys.

287
00:13:44,991 --> 00:13:48,536
Richie, here's the deal.

288
00:13:48,620 --> 00:13:50,747
Nobody's into the whole camp thing.

289
00:13:50,829 --> 00:13:52,206
You're making too many rules,

290
00:13:52,290 --> 00:13:53,958
and everybody just wants to have fun.

291
00:13:54,041 --> 00:13:57,878
Yeah, Richie, these little
piggies went to the market,

292
00:13:57,962 --> 00:14:02,717
and they all came home
with smiles on their faces.

293
00:14:02,801 --> 00:14:06,179
This is not what we do at camp.

294
00:14:06,262 --> 00:14:09,390
Come on, everyone,
let's go craft with pine cones.

295
00:14:09,474 --> 00:14:13,520
[all groan]

296
00:14:13,603 --> 00:14:16,564
Any chance they're going
to collect their own pine cones?

297
00:14:19,025 --> 00:14:20,943
None at all.

298
00:14:24,155 --> 00:14:25,990
Okay, campers,

299
00:14:26,073 --> 00:14:28,409
who's ready to have some Bohawk fun?

300
00:14:31,245 --> 00:14:35,750
"I am, and thanks for being
the best camp leader ever."

301
00:14:35,834 --> 00:14:37,918
[murmuring]

302
00:14:38,002 --> 00:14:39,420
Have you ever seen him like this?

303
00:14:39,504 --> 00:14:40,880
No.

304
00:14:40,963 --> 00:14:45,926
What a rapid five-minute descent
into madness.

305
00:14:46,010 --> 00:14:49,723
Richie, I need to talk to you.

306
00:14:49,806 --> 00:14:51,725
Anything you need to say to me

307
00:14:51,808 --> 00:14:55,978
you can say in front of them.

308
00:14:56,062 --> 00:15:01,484
Listen, I know you're upset
because the campers left, but...

309
00:15:01,568 --> 00:15:04,237
you kept making them do stuff
they didn't want to do.

310
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:06,865
But they didn't do
a single Bohawk activity.

311
00:15:06,947 --> 00:15:08,908
But they weren't at Camp Bohawk.

312
00:15:08,991 --> 00:15:11,327
They were at the coolest house
in the world,

313
00:15:11,411 --> 00:15:12,871
and you were showing them snails.

314
00:15:12,953 --> 00:15:15,289
When you have
your own personal water park,

315
00:15:15,373 --> 00:15:17,876
nobody cares about your snails.

316
00:15:17,958 --> 00:15:21,880
I guess I was just trying to
give them the experience we had.

317
00:15:21,962 --> 00:15:25,717
Right, and what was the
number one rule at Camp Bohawk?

318
00:15:25,800 --> 00:15:29,178
Never go in the shower without flip-flops.

319
00:15:29,262 --> 00:15:31,514
Okay, what was rule number two?

320
00:15:31,598 --> 00:15:33,516
Always have fun.

321
00:15:33,600 --> 00:15:36,644
Exactly, and snails aren't fun, Richie.

322
00:15:36,728 --> 00:15:38,897
They're just not. Ask anyone.

323
00:15:38,979 --> 00:15:40,732
Even the pine cones will tell you.

324
00:15:44,235 --> 00:15:46,863
"She's right.

325
00:15:46,946 --> 00:15:51,451
And nothing says thank you
like a brand-new credit card."

326
00:15:54,203 --> 00:15:57,290
I guess when I think back,
the best times at Camp Bohawk

327
00:15:57,373 --> 00:15:59,834
weren't doing what was planned.
They were--

328
00:15:59,918 --> 00:16:02,002
The clay fight we got into in ceramics?

329
00:16:02,086 --> 00:16:03,630
That was awesome.

330
00:16:03,713 --> 00:16:06,006
I was gonna say
the water fights we got into

331
00:16:06,090 --> 00:16:07,467
when there was a heat wave.

332
00:16:07,550 --> 00:16:08,968
- Amazing.
- [chuckles]

333
00:16:09,051 --> 00:16:11,805
Wait, I have an idea.

334
00:16:11,888 --> 00:16:14,348
Does it involve the pine cones?

335
00:16:14,432 --> 00:16:16,768
Yes.

336
00:16:16,851 --> 00:16:19,228
But my backup plan doesn't.

337
00:16:19,312 --> 00:16:22,398
Then let's go with the backup plan.

338
00:16:22,482 --> 00:16:24,400
[cha-ching]

339
00:16:28,613 --> 00:16:31,407
[blows nose]

340
00:16:31,491 --> 00:16:33,409
[computer chimes]

341
00:16:36,162 --> 00:16:38,164
Email from Harvard?

342
00:16:38,247 --> 00:16:40,625
Oh, no.

343
00:16:40,708 --> 00:16:42,752
[taps key]

344
00:16:42,836 --> 00:16:44,337
"Upon reading your letter,

345
00:16:44,420 --> 00:16:47,256
we've decided Harvard is
the best place for you."

346
00:16:47,340 --> 00:16:48,549
What?

347
00:16:48,633 --> 00:16:50,384
Admitted immediately?

348
00:16:50,468 --> 00:16:52,595
It happened! It finally happened!

349
00:16:52,679 --> 00:16:54,848
Take that, universe!

350
00:16:54,931 --> 00:16:56,474
You heard about my chicken helmet.

351
00:16:56,557 --> 00:16:58,309
I got accepted into Harvard.

352
00:16:58,392 --> 00:17:01,521
[gasps]
Honey, I'm so proud of you!

353
00:17:01,604 --> 00:17:04,816
Somehow that letter you wrote got me in.

354
00:17:04,899 --> 00:17:06,275
Thank you, thank you, thank you!

355
00:17:06,359 --> 00:17:09,946
[chuckles]

356
00:17:10,029 --> 00:17:12,406
Excuse me, Harper Rich?

357
00:17:12,490 --> 00:17:14,909
Harper "Just got into Harvard" Rich?

358
00:17:14,993 --> 00:17:16,410
Who are you?

359
00:17:16,494 --> 00:17:19,455
I'm Dr. Wright-Ihlenfeld from Harvard.

360
00:17:19,539 --> 00:17:20,915
Oh, you got here fast.

361
00:17:20,999 --> 00:17:22,291
Well, it's a pleasure to meet you.

362
00:17:22,375 --> 00:17:23,835
I can't wait to study at Harvard.

363
00:17:23,918 --> 00:17:27,505
Oh, sweetie,
you're not studying at Harvard.

364
00:17:27,588 --> 00:17:29,423
Harvard is studying you.

365
00:17:29,507 --> 00:17:31,968
Huh?

366
00:17:32,051 --> 00:17:34,512
Th-there must be some mistake.

367
00:17:34,595 --> 00:17:36,931
We read your letter. There's no mistake.

368
00:17:37,015 --> 00:17:39,017
Grab her, boys.

369
00:17:39,099 --> 00:17:40,852
Dad, do something!

370
00:17:40,935 --> 00:17:42,770
I am so proud, honey.

371
00:17:42,854 --> 00:17:46,357
Hang on--before you take her,
let me take a picture.

372
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:47,734
[camera shutter clicks]

373
00:17:47,817 --> 00:17:49,819
Oh, congratulations, Harp.

374
00:17:49,903 --> 00:17:52,739
You're always gonna remember this moment.

375
00:17:52,822 --> 00:17:54,574
I'm afraid she won't have any memory

376
00:17:54,657 --> 00:17:56,784
after the experiments we're doing on her.

377
00:17:56,868 --> 00:17:59,286
[screams]

378
00:17:59,370 --> 00:18:01,205
Please don't take me to Harvard!

379
00:18:01,288 --> 00:18:03,457
[sobbing]
Please!

380
00:18:03,541 --> 00:18:07,211
On behalf of Harvard and
the medical community at large,

381
00:18:07,294 --> 00:18:09,047
thank you for letting us have her.

382
00:18:09,129 --> 00:18:13,051
I'm just happy I could help
make her dreams come true.

383
00:18:13,133 --> 00:18:17,013
Daddy!

384
00:18:20,558 --> 00:18:22,518
[cha-ching]

385
00:18:22,602 --> 00:18:24,854
Oh, great. Crates.

386
00:18:24,938 --> 00:18:26,731
This scares me.

387
00:18:28,357 --> 00:18:32,570
At this point, everything scares me.

388
00:18:32,653 --> 00:18:34,321
Welcome back, campers.

389
00:18:34,405 --> 00:18:36,616
Time for our last activity.

390
00:18:36,699 --> 00:18:38,826
[all groan]

391
00:18:38,910 --> 00:18:42,413
I know we got off to a bad start,

392
00:18:42,496 --> 00:18:46,960
but I think you guys
are gonna have a lot of fun.

393
00:18:47,043 --> 00:18:51,130
All right, everyone, open your crates.

394
00:18:53,091 --> 00:18:54,550
Meatballs?

395
00:18:54,634 --> 00:18:58,096
Meatball fight!

396
00:18:59,597 --> 00:19:01,766
[laughter]

397
00:19:04,894 --> 00:19:07,187
Watch the cubicles!

398
00:19:07,271 --> 00:19:10,483
[rock music]

399
00:19:10,566 --> 00:19:18,491
♪ ♪

400
00:19:26,415 --> 00:19:28,626
[laughs]
Okay.

401
00:19:28,709 --> 00:19:30,795
Yeah.

402
00:19:37,677 --> 00:19:40,346
Boom goes the meatballs!

403
00:19:40,429 --> 00:19:41,597
Whoo!

404
00:19:41,681 --> 00:19:43,975
[applause]

405
00:19:44,058 --> 00:19:45,768
That was amazing.

406
00:19:45,852 --> 00:19:48,604
Where I come from,
after the meatball fight,

407
00:19:48,688 --> 00:19:50,648
we spit on the loser's face.

408
00:19:50,731 --> 00:19:53,651
But maybe we should just high-five.

409
00:19:53,734 --> 00:19:55,736
Take that and that!

410
00:19:55,820 --> 00:19:59,365
Revenge is a dish best served
with a side of meatballs!

411
00:19:59,448 --> 00:20:00,867
- [both] Murray!
- Stop!

412
00:20:00,950 --> 00:20:02,242
I'm done. I'm done.

413
00:20:02,326 --> 00:20:03,494
You can let me go.

414
00:20:03,577 --> 00:20:06,497
I'm cool.

415
00:20:06,580 --> 00:20:07,874
Take that!

416
00:20:07,957 --> 00:20:10,543
Who's laughing now, Abramowitzes?

417
00:20:10,626 --> 00:20:11,961
Enough!

418
00:20:12,045 --> 00:20:14,672
I'm cool. I'm cool.

419
00:20:14,755 --> 00:20:16,757
- [sighs]
- You did it, Richie.

420
00:20:16,841 --> 00:20:19,802
You created memories
of a lifetime for those kids.

421
00:20:19,886 --> 00:20:21,470
And one fully grown Swede.

422
00:20:21,554 --> 00:20:23,472
By the way, Richie,
if you are off to the market,

423
00:20:23,556 --> 00:20:25,058
- we are out of--
- Meatballs?

424
00:20:25,141 --> 00:20:29,103
I was going to say milk,
but yeah, meatballs too.

425
00:20:30,813 --> 00:20:32,023
Thanks, Darcy.

426
00:20:32,106 --> 00:20:33,315
You were right.

427
00:20:33,399 --> 00:20:37,570
This is way more fun than snails.

428
00:20:37,653 --> 00:20:38,821
[cha-ching]

429
00:20:38,905 --> 00:20:40,447
A meatball fight,

430
00:20:40,531 --> 00:20:44,660
because there is no other way to have fun.

431
00:20:49,082 --> 00:20:53,753
I...hate...Harvard.

